 their decline in the late-eighteenth century, tens of thousands of students passed through the colleges. Traditionally, these institutions were treated within limiting denominational and national contexts. This collection, at once building on and transcending inherited historiographies, explores the colleges' institutional interconnectivity and their interlocking roles as instruments of regional communities, dynastic interests and international Catholicism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCatholic universities and collegesxHistoryxEurope. 0aCatholic universities and collegeszEuropexHistory. 0aLearning and scholarshipzEuropexHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aCardinal Giovanni Morone.  aCatholic communities.  aCatholic students.  aCatholic territories.  aCollegium Germanicum.  aDutch Catholics.  aIreland.  aMaronite college.  aPropaganda Fide.  aProtestant reformers.  aProtestants.  aSociety of Jesus.  aStuart monarchy.  acollege-trained clergy.  ainternational interests.  apapal politics.  asocial history.  atransnational interests.  auniversity historiography.1 aChambers, Liam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChambers, Liam, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFink, Urban, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrijhoff, Willem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGirard, Aurélien, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKelly, James E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarks, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO'Connor, Thomas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aO’Connor, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.l